===Group F===
{{Main|2026 FIFA World Cup Group F}}

The [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] faced [[Japan national football team|Japan]] in the opener. In the first half, neither team scored.<ref>Horswill, Chloe (June 14, 2026). [https://theanalyst.com/articles/netherlands-vs-japan-stats-world-cup-2026 "Netherlands 2-2 Japan Stats: Kamada Snatches Dramatic Late Draw to Complete Comeback"]. ''Opta Analyst''. Retrieved June 15, 2026.</ref> Afterward, the match took a turn when [[Virgil van Dijk|Virgil van Dijk's]] header sealed the Dutch's opening goal, but [[Keito Nakamura]] equalized seven minutes later. [[Crysencio Summerville]] restored the lead not too long after, but the Netherlands conceded an equalizer after [[Kōki Ogawa (footballer)|Kōki Ogawa's]] header bounced off [[Daichi Kamada]] into the net right before stoppage time.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Athletic |first=The |date=June 14, 2026 |title=Japan come from behind twice to draw with Netherlands in brilliant World Cup 2026 match: Live updates and reaction |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/live-blogs/netherlands-vs-japan-live-updates-world-cup-2026-score-result/FruSpta6REdO/ |access-date=June 15, 2026 |website=The Athletic |language=en-US}}</ref> Between [[Sweden men's national football team|Sweden]] and [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]], the two nations exchanged goals in the first half: two from Swedes [[Yasin Ayari]] and [[Alexander Isak]], and one from Tunisia's [[Omar Rekik]]. In the second half, Tunisia conceded from [[Viktor Gyökeres]] and [[Mattias Svanberg]], including Ayari's second in stoppage time. Additionally, Svanberg's goal was initially ruled [[Offside (association football)|offside]], but was reinstated after VAR confirmed that Isak had slightly tipped the ball with his foot, eliminating the offside in question.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Yasin Ayari brace helps Sweden overwhelm Tunisia |url=https://fieldlevelmedia.com/recap/yasin-ayari-brace-helps-sweden-overwhelm-tunisia/ |access-date=June 15, 2026 |website=Field Level Media - Professional sports content solutions {{!}} FLM |language=en-US}}</ref> Following the match, Tunisia's head coach, [[Sabri Lamouchi]], was dismissed, and replaced by [[Hervé Renard]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=June 16, 2026 |title=World Cup manager change: Tunisia appoint head coach Herve Renard to replace Sabri Lamouchi |url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/news/tunisia-manager-sabri-lamouchi-world-cup-sweden-fired/ |access-date=June 16, 2026 |website=CBS Sports |language=en}}</ref>

The Netherlands scored twice against Sweden in the first half with [[Brian Brobbey]] scoring a brace within the first twenty minutes of the match. [[Cody Gakpo]] followed up with a brace of his own within the first ten minutes of the second half. Despite [[Anthony Elanga]] scoring on the 59th minute, which turned out to be the 100th goal in this year's tournament, [[Crysencio Summerville]] scored near the end of the match to top off the Dutch's massive win against the Swedes.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Miller |first=Nick |last2=Jones |first2=Andy |last3=Anka |first3=Carl |last4=Whitehead |first4=Jacob |date=June 20, 2026 |title=Netherlands hit five past Sweden. Does this huge win make them World Cup contenders? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/7370754/2026/06/20/netherlands-sweden-result-world-cup-gakpo-brobbey/ |access-date=June 20, 2026 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Japan scored in the 4th minute from a [[Daichi Kamada]] tap-in inside the 6-yard box. [[Ayase Ueda]] raised the score to 2–0 from a long-range shot to the bottom corner. In the second half, [[Junya Itō]] and Ueda completed a 4–0 win against Tunisia, eliminating them from the World Cup.

