===Group H===
{{Main|2026 FIFA World Cup Group H}}

[[Cape Verde national football team|Cape Verde]] made its World Cup debut against [[Spain national football team|Spain]] and held the heavy favorite to the first goalless draw of the tournament. Despite dominating possession and shots, Spain was unable to find a breakthrough as Cape Verde's defense and [[Vozinha]]'s goalkeeping efforts kept the game scoreless,<ref>[https://www.si.com/soccer/spain-player-ratings-vs-cabo-verde-world-cup-opener-springs-huge-surprise "Spain Player Ratings vs. Cabo Verde: La Roja Left Frustrated Against Minnows"]. ''SI''. June 15, 2026. Retrieved June 15, 2026.</ref> earning Cape Verde its first-ever World Cup point. [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]]'s [[Abdulelah Al-Amri]] scored first against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]], with [[Mohammed Al-Owais]] and the Saudi defense holding off Uruguay, but Uruguay regained composure and equalized with [[Maximiliano Araújo|Maximiliano Araújo's]] goal near the end of the match.<ref>[https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/13552712/world-cup-2026-saudi-arabia-1-1-uruguay-maxi-araujo-levels-late-but-goalkeeper-mohammed-al-owais-is-the-hero "World Cup 2026: Saudi Arabia 1-1 Uruguay - Maxi Araujo levels late but goalkeeper Mohammed Al-Owais is the hero"]. ''Sky Sports''. Retrieved June 16, 2026.</ref>

Against Saudi Arabia, Spain scored for the first time in the tournament after [[Lamine Yamal]], in the 10th minute, scored his first World Cup goal, while [[Mikel Oyarzabal]] followed up with a brace before the 25th minute. In the 49th minute, [[Hassan Al-Tambakti]] accidentally scored an own goal to make it 4–0 to Spain, while Saudi Arabia had its only shot on target with ten minutes to go.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Brotherton |first=Live ReportingAlex |title=Spain vs Saudi Arabia LIVE: Watch FIFA World Cup Group H TV stream, score, commentary & updates, Sutton's predictions |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c1eyg6lq5wvt |access-date=June 22, 2026 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Cape Verde scored its first ever World Cup goal thanks to a free kick from 30 yards out by [[Kevin Pina (footballer)|Kevin Pina]]. Despite Uruguay reclaiming the lead by efforts from [[Maximiliano Araújo]] and [[Agustín Canobbio]] before half-time, the Cape Verdeans scored an equalizer in the 61th minute by [[Hélio Varela]]. With the final score 2–2, Cape Verde earned their second consecutive point.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Murray |first=Ewan |date=June 22, 2026 |title=Cape Verde produce another World Cup shock as Varela strike seals Uruguay draw |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2026/jun/22/cape-verde-uruguay-world-cup-group-h-match-report |access-date=June 22, 2026 |work=The Guardian |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

