===Individual and team awards===
{{See also|FIFA World Cup awards}}

The following awards are to be presented at the end of the tournament.

*Golden Boot: Awarded to the tournament's top goal scorer.
*Golden Glove: Awarded to the tournament's best goalkeeper.
*Golden Ball: Awarded to the best overall player of the tournament.
*FIFA Young Player Award: Awarded to the best overall player of the tournament under the age of 21.
*FIFA Fair Play Trophy: Awarded to the team with the best disciplinary record that reached the knockout stage.

Additionally, a "superior player of the match" is presented after each fixture to the player deemed to have delivered the most outstanding performance and greatest impact in that match. The recipient is selected through a public online vote conducted by FIFA. The award is sponsored by [[Michelob Ultra]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/articles/michelob-ultra-superior-player-of-match-winner |title=Michelob Ultra Superior Player of the Match - every winner |website=FIFA |date=June 11, 2026 |language=en |access-date=June 15, 2026}}</ref>

==Marketing==

===Branding===
[[File:2026 FIFA WC countdown clock Paseo de la Reforma.jpg|thumb|Countdown clock on [[Paseo de la Reforma]], Mexico City|alt=A freestanding digital clock with Fifa branding placed on the sidewalk.]]

The official emblem and brand identity was unveiled on May 17, 2023, at the [[Griffith Observatory]] in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]; its basic form consists of a stacked "26" with an image of the [[FIFA World Cup Trophy]] in front of it, designed to be adaptable to different backdrops. This is the first time that the trophy has been depicted in a World Cup emblem as a photo, as opposed to a stylized representation.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Cook |first=Glenn |date=May 17, 2023 |title=FIFA Unveils Logo For 2026 World Cup in North America |url=https://news.sportslogos.net/2023/05/17/fifa-unveils-visual-identity-for-2026-world-cup-in-north-america/soccer/ |access-date=May 18, 2023 |website=SportsLogos.Net News |archive-date=May 18, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230518041252/https://news.sportslogos.net/2023/05/17/fifa-unveils-visual-identity-for-2026-world-cup-in-north-america/soccer/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{cite web |last=Cook |first=Glenn |date=May 18, 2023 |title='Is That It?': Reaction to 2026 World Cup Logo Swift, Overwhelmingly Negative |url=https://news.sportslogos.net/2023/05/18/is-that-it-reaction-to-2026-world-cup-logo-swift-overwhelmingly-negative/soccer/ |access-date=May 18, 2023 |website=SportsLogos.Net News |archive-date=May 18, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230518200435/https://news.sportslogos.net/2023/05/18/is-that-it-reaction-to-2026-world-cup-logo-swift-overwhelmingly-negative/soccer/ |url-status=live}}</ref> The next day, FIFA unveiled variants of the emblem for each of the host cities, which feature color variants and designs that reflect local landscapes or culture. For example, the Los Angeles features a stylized sun and wave, Monterrey features the [[Cerro de la Silla]] mountain, and Toronto features the city skyline and the [[CN Tower]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Cook |first=Glenn |date=May 19, 2023 |title=FIFA, Host Cities Roll Out Specific Branding for 2026 World Cup |url=https://news.sportslogos.net/2023/05/19/fifa-host-cities-roll-out-specific-branding-for-2026-world-cup/soccer/ |access-date=November 25, 2023 |website=SportsLogos.Net News |archive-date=November 25, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231125024742/https://news.sportslogos.net/2023/05/19/fifa-host-cities-roll-out-specific-branding-for-2026-world-cup/soccer/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Unprecedented Host City brands launched to bring FIFA World Cup 26 destinations to life |url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/media-releases/origin1904-p.cxm.fifa.com/unprecedented-host-city-brands-launched-to-bring-fifa-world-cup-26-tm |access-date=November 25, 2023 |website=www.fifa.com |archive-date=November 25, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231125024745/https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/media-releases/origin1904-p.cxm.fifa.com/unprecedented-host-city-brands-launched-to-bring-fifa-world-cup-26-tm |url-status=live}}</ref>

Reaction to the logo from the initial unveiling was largely negative, with many feeling that the design was either unfinished or uncreative compared to the emblems of past FIFA World Cup tournaments. By contrast, [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]] player [[Jesús Ferreira]] described the emblem as "beautiful".<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Shah |first=Parshva |date=May 18, 2023 |title='It's beautiful' – USMNT striker Jesus Ferreira disagrees with people who hate FIFA's World Cup 2026 logo |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/it-s-beautiful-usmnt-striker-jesus-ferreira-disagrees-with-people-who-hate-fifa-s-world-cup-2026-logo/blt5889b73a50f9d6bc |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230518232153/https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/it-s-beautiful-usmnt-striker-jesus-ferreira-disagrees-with-people-who-hate-fifa-s-world-cup-2026-logo/blt5889b73a50f9d6bc |archive-date=May 18, 2023 |access-date=May 19, 2023 |website=[[Goal.com]] }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Borg |first=Simon |date=May 18, 2023 |title=Fans rip FIFA World Cup 2026 logo after official reveal for men's tournament in USA, Mexico and Canada |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/ca/soccer/news/fifa-world-cup-2026-logo-reveal-usa-mexico-canada/x2dpsllp98zqaj2bkxwsdqhi |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230519060838/https://www.sportingnews.com/ca/soccer/news/fifa-world-cup-2026-logo-reveal-usa-mexico-canada/x2dpsllp98zqaj2bkxwsdqhi |archive-date=May 19, 2023 |access-date=May 19, 2023 |website=Sporting News}}</ref>

[[File:WorldCup2026lposter.jpg|thumb|upright|Official poster]]

In March and April 2025, FIFA unveiled a set of 16 posters representing each of the 2026 World Cup host cities. The posters, designed by local artists, were intended to reflect the "distinct identity and heritage" of each host city.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://inside.fifa.com/organisation/news/unique-local-spirit-official-world-cup-26-host-city-posters |title=Unique local spirit highlighted in Official FIFA World Cup 26 Host City Posters |publisher=FIFA |date=March 17, 2025 |access-date=May 14, 2026}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.footyheadlines.com/2025/04/the-2026-wc-posters.html |title=The 2026 World Cup Posters Revealed |date=April 22, 2025|access-date=April 22, 2025 |website=footyheadlines.com/}}</ref> On March 3, 2026, the official poster was unveiled. For the first time, three artists combined their artistic styles to create the official poster: Carson Ting (Canada), Minerva GM (Mexico), and Hank Willis Thomas (United States).<ref name="Official posters">{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/official-posters |title=Official Tournament Poster|access-date=March 3, 2026 |date=March 3, 2026 |website=FIFA}}</ref>

===Broadcasting rights===
{{Main|2026 FIFA World Cup broadcasting rights}}

On February 12, 2015, FIFA renewed the United States and Canadian broadcasting rights contracts for [[Fox Sports (United States)|Fox Sports]] (US English), [[Telemundo Deportes]] (US Spanish), and [[Bell Media]] (Canada) to cover the 2026 World Cup, without accepting any other bids. A report in ''[[The New York Times]]'' asserted that this extension was intended as compensation for the rescheduling of the [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022 World Cup]] to November–December rather than its traditional June–July scheduling, as it created considerable conflicts with [[Major professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada|major professional sports leagues]] that are normally in their offseasons during the World Cup.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Deitsch |first=Richard |date=February 12, 2015 |title=FIFA grants Fox, Telemundo U.S. TV rights for World Cup through 2026 |magazine=Sports Illustrated |url=https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/2015/02/12/fifa-fox-usa-tv-rights-world-cup-2026-telemundo |access-date=June 26, 2018 |archive-date=April 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408163522/https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/2015/02/12/fifa-fox-usa-tv-rights-world-cup-2026-telemundo |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Sandomir |first=Richard |date=February 26, 2015 |title=Why FIFA Made Deal With Fox for 2026 Cup |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/27/sports/soccer/why-fifa-made-deal-with-fox-for-2026-cup.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408163525/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/27/sports/soccer/why-fifa-made-deal-with-fox-for-2026-cup.html |archive-date=April 8, 2020 |access-date=June 26, 2018 |work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref name="cangloberights">{{Cite news |date=February 12, 2015 |title=FIFA extending TV deals through 2026 World Cup with CTV, TSN and RDS |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/soccer/fifa-extending-tv-deals-through-2026-world-cup-with-ctv-tsn-and-rds/article22965136/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160410181248/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/soccer/fifa-extending-tv-deals-through-2026-world-cup-with-ctv-tsn-and-rds/article22965136/ |archive-date=April 10, 2016}}</ref>

[[File:TSN Jack Poole Broadcast Studio (2026) closeup.jpg|thumb|[[Bell Media]] broadcast studio located at [[Jack Poole Plaza]] in Vancouver. [[The Sports Network|TSN]] is the primary broadcaster, while select matches are on [[CTV Television Network|CTV]] and [[Crave (streaming service)|Crave]] in Canada.]]
The [[International Broadcast Centre|International Broadcast Center]] (IBC) will be located at the [[Kay Bailey Hutchison Convention Center]] in [[Dallas]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Rosenbaum |first=Steven |date=December 11, 2024 |title=Dallas approves $15 million spending to serve as media hub for the 2026 FIFA World Cup |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/texas/news/dallas-texas-2026-fifa-world-cup-international-broadcast-center-media-hub/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241212105138/https://www.cbsnews.com/texas/news/dallas-texas-2026-fifa-world-cup-international-broadcast-center-media-hub/ |archive-date=December 12, 2024 |website=CBS News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fox4news.com/news/2026-fifa-world-cup-international-broadcast-center-will-be-dallas |title=2026 FIFA World Cup International Broadcast Center will be in Dallas |date=December 11, 2024 |publisher=FOX News|archive-date=December 11, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241211232758/https://www.fox4news.com/news/2026-fifa-world-cup-international-broadcast-center-will-be-dallas|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=March 5, 2025 |title=FIFA World Cup 26™ International Broadcast Centre to be hosted in Dallas |url=https://inside.fifa.com/organisation/news/world-cup-26-international-broadcast-centre-dallas |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250318125506/https://inside.fifa.com/organisation/news/world-cup-26-international-broadcast-centre-dallas |archive-date=March 18, 2025 |access-date=March 5, 2025 |website=FIFA}}</ref> Bell Media constructed a broadcast studio at [[Jack Poole Plaza]] in Vancouver for the tournament (mirroring an arrangement used by Fox during the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup]]), which will operate through the final match played in Vancouver on July 7.<ref>{{Cite web |title=TSN's FIFA World Cup broadcast studio is taking over Jack Poole Plaza |url=https://dailyhive.com/vancouver/tsn-ctv-fifa-world-cup-broadcast-studio-jack-poole-plaza-vancouver-construction |access-date=June 12, 2026 |website=Daily Hive |language=en}}</ref>

On January 8, 2026, FIFA signed a deal to make [[TikTok]] a "preferred platform" for World Cup video content. As part of the agreement, broadcasters may stream parts of matches at a dedicated hub on the TikTok app.<ref>{{cite web |date=January 8, 2026 |title=FIFA picks TikTok as video content partner at 2026 World Cup |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/47552269/fifa-tiktok-video-content-partner-2026-world-cup |work=ESPN |access-date=March 18, 2026 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> FIFA then made a similar "preferred platform" deal with [[YouTube]] on March 17, allowing broadcasters to stream select matches in full on their respective YouTube channels, as well as stream the first 10 minutes of every match on the platform as "an appetizer encouraging young fans then to watch on traditional channels".<ref>{{cite web |date=March 17, 2026 |title=YouTube, FIFA agree to live broadcast deal for World Cup |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/48231331/youtube-fifa-agree-live-broadcast-deal-world-cup |work=ESPN |access-date=March 18, 2026 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref>

A number of internet content creators have also been involved in coverage of the tournament; in Brazil, [[Casimiro (streamer)|Casimiro Miguel]]'s [[CazéTV]] renewed its digital rights to the World Cup in Brazil, streaming all matches on its YouTube channel.<ref>{{Cite web |date=March 19, 2026 |title=Após parceria com YouTube, Fifa confirma exclusividade digital da CazéTV no Brasil para Copa 2026 |url=https://maquinadoesporte.com.br/midia/apos-parceria-com-youtube-fifa-confirma-exclusividade-digital-de-cazetv-para-copa-2026/ |access-date=March 22, 2026 |website=Máquina do Esporte |language=pt-BR |last=Filho |first=Adalberto Leister|trans-title=Following a partnership with YouTube, FIFA confirms CazéTV's digital exclusivity in Brazil for the 2026 World Cup}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Laloni |first=Marco |date=March 13, 2026 |title=YouTube e CazéTV lançam o filme publicitário "A Agente do Hexa" |url=https://www.mktesportivo.com/2026/03/em-parceria-com-a-cazetv-youtube-lanca-o-filme-publicitario-a-agente-do-hexa/ |access-date=March 22, 2026 |website=MKT Esportivo|trans-title=In partnership with CazéTV, YouTube launches the advertising film "The Agent of the Hexa" (referring to Brazil's sixth World Cup victory)|language=pt-BR}}</ref> [[IShowSpeed]] has conducted streams from matches during the tournament, and later reached an agreement with Fox Sports to offer [[Altcast|altcasts]] of selected matches on [[Fox One]] and its YouTube channel featuring his streams combined with the Fox telecasts.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Binder |first=Matt |date=June 15, 2026 |title=Video shows IShowSpeed meeting Mayor Mamdani at World Cup |url=https://mashable.com/entertainment/ishowspeed-meets-nyc-mayor-zohran-mamdani-at-world-cup |access-date=June 18, 2026 |website=Mashable |language=en}}</ref><ref name="auto3">{{Cite magazine |last=Parham |first=Jason |title=Streamer IShowSpeed Is Gen Z's ESPN |url=https://www.wired.com/story/big-interview-ishowspeed-world-cup/ |access-date=June 18, 2026 |magazine=Wired |language=en-US |issn=1059-1028}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Kleen |first=Brendon |date=June 18, 2026 |title=Star content creator iShowSpeed strikes deal with FIFA, Fox, and YouTube to stream live World Cup games |url=https://awfulannouncing.com/fox/ishowspeed-deal-stream-live-fifa-world-cup-games.html |access-date=June 18, 2026 |website=Awful Announcing |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name="auto3"/>

