====Video games====
{{Main|FIFA World Cup video games#2026 FIFA World Cup}}

On October 2, 2025, FIFA announced the video game ''[[FIFA Heroes]]'', scheduled for release in 2026 on [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[Nintendo Switch]], [[PlayStation]], and [[Xbox]] platforms.<ref>{{Cite web |title=FIFA World Cup 26™ mascots make video game debut as playable characters in FIFA® Heroes |url=https://inside.fifa.com/organisation/news/world-cup-26-mascots-make-video-game-debut-playable-characters-fifa-heroes |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20251002132023/https://inside.fifa.com/organisation/news/world-cup-26-mascots-make-video-game-debut-playable-characters-fifa-heroes |archive-date=October 2, 2025 |access-date=October 15, 2025 |website=FIFA}}</ref>

In May 2026, the ''[[Football Manager 26]]'' video game also announced the addition of licensed 2026 FIFA World Cup content.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Chase FIFA World Cup 2026™ Glory: International Management arrives in FM26 |url=https://www.footballmanager.com/fm26/features/chase-fifa-world-cup-2026tm-glory-international-management-arrives-fm26 |access-date=May 20, 2026 |website=Football Manager}}</ref>

In December 2025, [[Netflix]] announced a new simulation-type game featuring the World Cup, produced by Delphi Interactive and Refactor Games.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Changing The Game: FIFA Arrives on Netflix Games in Time for FIFA World Cup 2026 |url=https://www.netflix.com/tudum/articles/fifa-mens-world-cup-2026-game-on-netflix |access-date=May 22, 2025 |website=TUDUM |quote=The game, developed and published by Delphi Interactive, allows Netflix members to experience the emotion and drama of the (World Cup) tournament in its purest, most joyful form}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Forbes-Calvin |first=Alex |date=February 9, 2026 |title=Meet Delphi Interactive, the publisher/developer behind the new FIFA game |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/meet-delphi-interactive-the-publisherdeveloper-behind-the-new-fifa-game |access-date=May 19, 2026 |website=GamesIndustry.biz |quote=For FIFA, that includes Refactor Games, based at Delphi's LA headquarters, part-owned by Delphi and backed by venture capital giant A16z's Speedrun fund}}</ref> In May 2026, it was announced the Netflix-published game would be titled "''FIFA World Cup – Launch Edition''" and would be released in June 2026.<ref name=":7">{{Cite web |date=May 28, 2026 |title=FIFA unveils updated Digital Football Strategy to connect partners and platforms across global gaming and esports ecosystem |url=https://inside.fifa.com/organisation/media-releases/origin1904-p.cxm.fifa.com/digital-football-strategy-connect-partners-platforms-global-gaming-esports-ecosystem |access-date=May 29, 2026 |website=FIFA}}</ref>

In the same May 2026 announcement, FIFA also confirmed that they would adopt a non-exclusive "Digital Football" ecosystem, with games of various genres adopting the FIFA license. Alongside the new World Cup game, were mentioned ''FIFA Heroes'', ''FIFA Rivals, [[List of Roblox games|FIFA Super Soccer]], [[Football Manager]], [[eFootball]]'' and ''[[Rocket League]],'' with more games joining the ecosystem in the following months.<ref name=":7" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Hicks |first=Jon |date=May 28, 2026 |title=FIFA announces new "Digital Football" vision, an ecosystem of games from multiple publishers and developers |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/fifa-announces-new-digital-football-vision-an-ecosystem-of-games-from-multiple-publishers-and-developers |access-date=May 29, 2026 |website=GamesIndustry.biz }}</ref>

====Other products====
[[File:FIFA_2026_Merch_Truck_at_Fisherman's_Wharf.jpg|thumb|260x260px|A pop-up truck selling FIFA 2026 merchandise at [[Fisherman's Wharf, San Francisco|Fisherman's Wharf, San Francisco, California]]]]
[[Panini Group|Panini]] sticker albums were again announced for the 2026 World Cup. Due to the expansion of the tournament, each pack now contains seven stickers as opposed to the usual 5. In the United States and Canada, a set of 12 stickers was reserved for stickers that could only be obtained from Coca-Cola bottles, with each bottle containing a sticker printed inside the label.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mackie |first=Andrew |date=May 19, 2026 |title=2026 FIFA World Cup Panini sticker tips, quirks and the most valuable items so far |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/7290962/2026/05/19/panini-2026-fifa-world-cup-stickers-most-valuable/ |access-date=May 20, 2026 |work=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In May 2026, it was announced that the 2026 World Cup would be Panini's second-to-last tournament with a sticker album, after FIFA announced that [[Fanatics, Inc.|Fanatics]] (via their [[Topps]] brand) would distribute collectables for FIFA tournaments from 2031.<ref>{{Cite web |title=FIFA to drop Panini for World Cup deal with Fanatics in 2031 |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/48701397/fifa-drop-panini-world-cup-deal-fanatics-2031 |access-date=May 20, 2026 |website=ESPN}}</ref>

In conjunction with the tournament, [[the Lego Group]] released a series of officially licensed FIFA World Cup 2026-themed construction sets. The collection included models of the FIFA World Cup Trophy, the official tournament emblem, a brick-built [[Adidas Trionda]] soccer ball containing a miniature stadium, and player-focused sets based on soccer players [[Lionel Messi]], [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], [[Kylian Mbappé]], and [[Vinícius Júnior]]. Several sets featured hidden references to the players' careers, alternative display poses, and commemorative World Cup-themed designs.<ref>{{cite news |title=11 Lego World Cup Sets You Don't Need to Be a Soccer Pro to Build |url=https://www.esquire.com/sports/a71165497/lego-world-cup-2026/ |work=Esquire |first=Angel |last=Madison |date=May 1, 2026 |access-date=June 8, 2026}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The FIFA World Cup 2026 is almost here, and Lego has some of the coolest World Cup merch we've ever seen |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/products-kit/the-fifa-world-cup-2026-is-one-week-away-and-these-lego-edition-sets-are-some-of-the-best-world-cup-merchandise-weve-seen |work=FourFourTwo |first=Paul |last=Brett |date=June 3, 2026 |access-date=June 8, 2026}}</ref> To promote the product line, Lego organized FIFA World Cup 2026-themed activations in several markets, including a soccer festival and pop-up experience in [[Singapore]]. The events featured interactive soccer challenges, soccer-themed Lego builds, displays of player-inspired models, and promotional giveaways tied to the World Cup collection.<ref>{{cite news |title=LEGO Brings FIFA World Cup 2026 Pop-Up and LEGO Editions Football Sets to Singapore |url=https://www.brandinginasia.com/lego-brings-fifa-world-cup-2026-pop-up-and-lego-editions-football-sets-to-singapore/ |work=Branding in Asia |author=BIA Staff |date=June 5, 2026 |access-date=June 8, 2026}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=LEGO Group launches FIFA World Cup 2026-themed football activations in Singapore |url=https://marketech-apac.com/lego-group-launches-fifa-world-cup-2026-themed-football-activations-in-singapore/ |work=MARKETECH APAC |first=Aliza |last=Carmona |date=June 5, 2026 |access-date=June 8, 2026}}</ref>

==Symbols==

===Mascots===
{{Main|Maple, Zayu and Clutch}}
{{See also|List of FIFA World Cup official mascots}}
[[File:2026 FIFA World Cup Mascots small.jpg|thumb|right|The tournament mascots: Maple the Moose, Zayu the Jaguar, and Clutch the Bald Eagle|alt=Refer to caption.]]

The official mascots of the tournament were revealed on September 25, 2025, and are [[Maple, Zayu and Clutch]]. Maple is a [[moose]], Zayu is a [[jaguar]], and Clutch is a [[bald eagle]], representing Canada, Mexico, and the United States, respectively.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Hernandez |first=Cesar |date=September 25, 2025 |title=Who are the 2026 World Cup mascots? Maple, Zayu and Clutch! |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/46377619/who-2026-fifa-world-cup-mascots-maple-zayu-clutch |access-date=September 25, 2025 |website=ESPN.com |language=en}}</ref> They were designed to reflect the cultural heritage of their respective countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/articles/clutch-maple-zayu-mascots-unveiled |title=Colourful trio of mascots unveiled for FIFA World Cup 26 |publisher=[[FIFA]] |access-date=September 25, 2025}}</ref>

===Match ball===
{{Main|Adidas Trionda}}
{{See also|List of FIFA World Cup official match balls}}
[[File:FIFA World Cup 2026 Draw Reception (54972841852).jpg|thumb|[[Adidas Trionda]], the match ball|242x242px|alt=The match ball displayed on a stand.]]

On May 2, 2025, reports surfaced that the match ball would be called [[Adidas Trionda]]. The design features red, green, and blue (the three colors representing Canada, Mexico, and the United States, respectively, and also featured on the host countries' flags), as well as a white wave connecting each of the colors, hence the name using the [[Spanish language|Spanish]] words for three (tri) and wave (onda).<ref>{{Cite web |last=Steiner |first=Ben |date=May 2, 2025 |title=FIFA World Cup 2026 'Trionda' Match Ball Leaks, Featuring U.S., Mexico and Canada Colors |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/fifa-world-cup-2026-trionda-match-ball-leak |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250502232842/https://www.si.com/soccer/fifa-world-cup-2026-trionda-match-ball-leak |archive-date=May 2, 2025 |magazine=Sports Illustrated}}</ref> The design also features the national symbols of the three host countries (a [[maple leaf]] for Canada, a [[Golden eagle#canadensis|golden eagle]] for Mexico, and a [[five-pointed star]] for the United States) as well as gold embellishments to represent the [[FIFA World Cup Trophy|World Cup Trophy]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=October 2, 2025 |title=FIFA celebrates launch of Official Match Ball of FIFA World Cup 26™: TRIONDA |url=https://inside.fifa.com/organisation/media-releases/fifa-celebrates-launch-official-match-ball-world-cup-26-trionda |access-date=October 2, 2025 |website=FIFA}}</ref>

On June 11, 2025, and in preparation for the 2026 FIFA World Cup, [[NASA]] conducted experiments aboard the International Space Station using soccer balls to study how mass distribution and embedded sensor technology affect ball motion and stability in microgravity. According to NASA, the research contributed to the development and evaluation of technologies used in the 2026 FIFA World Cup official match ball.<ref>{{cite web |title=Soccer Meets Space Science |url=https://www.nasa.gov/image-article/soccer-meets-space-science/ |publisher=NASA |access-date=June 20, 2026}}</ref>

===Music===
{{See also|Official FIFA World Cup 2026 Album|List of FIFA World Cup songs and anthems}}

The tournament's official instrumental theme music was composed by Zachary Aaron Golden. Throughout March 2025, FIFA released remixes of the theme for each host city by local producers.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Sáenz |first=Lissete Lanuza |date=February 27, 2025 |title=2026 FIFA World Cup Theme To Get a Different Remix For Every Host City |url=https://remezcla.com/sports/2026-fifa-world-cup-theme-to-get-a-different-remix-for-every-host-city/ |access-date=June 14, 2026 |website=Remezcla |language=en}}</ref>

The official song "[[Dai Dai]]" by Colombian singer [[Shakira]] and Nigerian singer [[Burna Boy]] was released on May 15, 2026,<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Roiz |first=Jessica |date=May 15, 2026 |title=Shakira & Burna Boy Shout Out Soccer Icons in Official 2026 FIFA World Cup Song 'Dai Dai' |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/latin/shakira-burna-boy-dai-dai-fifa-world-cup-song-1236247777/ |access-date=May 15, 2026 |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |language=en-US}}</ref> followed by the official anthem "[[DNA (More Than a Game)]]" by French producer [[David Guetta]], featuring Italian tenor [[Andrea Bocelli]], South Korean-American singer [[Ejae]], and American rapper [[Megan Thee Stallion]], on June 10, 2026.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Saponara |first=Michael |date=June 10, 2026 |title=Megan Thee Stallion, David Guetta, EJAE & Andrea Bocelli Team Up for FIFA World Cup 2026 Anthem 'DNA': Listen |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/megan-thee-stallion-david-guetta-ejae-andrea-bocelli-fifa-world-cup-dna-1236269793/ |access-date=June 11, 2026 |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |language=en-US}}</ref>

The official soundtrack album was released on June 5, 2026, with its first single "[[Lighter (Jelly Roll and Carín León song)|Lighter]]" by [[Jelly Roll (singer)|Jelly Roll]] and [[Carín León]] having been released on March 20, 2026; the song had garnered a mixed reception from listeners and critics, with some having falsely assumed that it was meant to be the tournament's official song before "Dai Dai" was released.<ref name="Conversation">{{Cite web |last=Keogh|first=Brent|date=March 26, 2026|title=A Bible Belt track without a pulse – it's no surprise fans hate the 2026 FIFA World Cup song Lighter|url=https://theconversation.com/a-bible-belt-track-without-a-pulse-its-no-surprise-fans-hate-the-2026-fifa-world-cup-song-lighter-279111|access-date=March 26, 2026|website=The Conversation|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Zeglinski|first1=Robert|title=Shakira is releasing a new World Cup song so we can forget the other terrible one|url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/2026/05/07/shakira-world-cup-song-teaser-better-jelly-roll-forget/89984860007/|work=For The Win|publisher=USA Today|date=May 7, 2026|access-date=June 10, 2026}}</ref><ref name=":02">{{Cite magazine |last=Balzano|first=Cata|date=June 3, 2026|title=These Are the Artists Who Will Be on the Official Album for the FIFA World Cup 2026|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/fifa-world-cup-2026-tracklist-1236263391/|access-date=June 12, 2026|magazine=Billboard|language=en-US}}</ref>

Instrumental song "[[Sirius (instrumental)|Sirius]]" by British [[rock music|rock]] band [[the Alan Parsons Project]] was used for the theme song for the entrances of the national teams before each game during the first matchday of the group stage.<ref>{{Cite web |title=The Chicago Bulls intro music to welcome Mexico and South Africa to the pitch is EPIC |url=https://www.foxsports.com/watch-vertical/fmc-2g4zwhtae8h4xnez |access-date=June 12, 2026 |website=www.foxsports.com |language=en-US}}</ref> This was changed to a remix of "Dai Dai" done by English electronic group [[Clean Bandit]] for the second matchday.{{citation needed|date=June 2026}}

==Controversies==
{{Main|List of 2026 FIFA World Cup controversies}}
Criticism of the tournament also included United States immigration and visa policies under the [[Second presidency of Donald Trump|Trump administration]], the participation of Iran amid an [[2026 Iran war|ongoing war waged by the United States and Israel]], FIFA's ticket pricing, labor, safety and transit issues in host cities. Escalating [[Mexican drug war|drug cartel violence in Mexico]] has also fueled speculative security concerns for the tournament, prompting the Mexican government to announce the deployment of nearly 100,000 security personnel to protect fans.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/ce8wjwyjndyo |title=World Cup 2026: Co-hosts Mexico plan to deploy 100,000 security personnel |date=March 6, 2026 |website=BBC Sport|access-date=March 10, 2026 |last=Poole |first=Harry}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=5 police officers shot dead in cartel-plagued part of Mexico as World Cup kicks off |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/police-officers-killed-mexico-world-cup-kicks-off/ |work=CBS News |date=June 11, 2026}}</ref> The Sport and Rights Alliance (SRA), including [[Human Rights Watch]] (HRW) and [[Amnesty International]]. Characterized the tournament as a form of [[sportswashing]].<ref>{{Cite news |last1=MacInnes |first1=Paul |last2=Ames |first2=Nick |date=April 27, 2026 |title=World Cup will be 'bonanza of sportswashing' under Trump, say human rights groups |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2026/apr/27/world-cup-bonanza-of-sportswashing-donald-trump-ice-human-rights |access-date=June 16, 2026 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

FIFA's used [[dynamic pricing]] for World Cup tickets for the first time.<ref name=":1" /> [[NJ Transit]] raised round-trip rail fares to [[MetLife Stadium]] from $13 to $150 (later reduced to $98) and officials closed pedestrian routes to the stadium.<ref>{{cite web | title=The U.S. Campaigned to host the World Cup. Now soccer fans will trade their countries' train system for the U.S.'s 'D' rated infrastructure | url=https://fortune.com/2026/05/25/fifa-infrastructure-market-tickets-investment/ |work=Fortune}}</ref><ref name="Wolfe">{{cite news | last1=Wolfe | first1=Alex | last2=Wilson | first2=Thomas | title=You Can Walk to the World Cup in New Jersey. But Should You? | work=The New York Times | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/07/opinion/world-cup-new-york-new-jersey-transit-walk.html }}</ref> New Jersey's final host Governor [[Mikie Sherrill]] blamed FIFA for the higher transportation costs and that they should subsidize it,<ref>https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cg73p124k07o</ref> as did [[Chuck Schumer]]. New York Governor [[Kathy Hochul]] wrote: "The World Cup should be as affordable and accessible as possible. Charging over $100 for a short train ride sounds awfully high to me." FIFA responded in shock while saying: "The original FIFA World Cup 2026 ⁠Host City Agreements signed in 2018 required free transportation for fans to all matches."<Ref>https://www.aljazeera.com/sports/2026/4/16/fifa-surprised-by-us-backlash-as-transport-costs-skyrocket-at-world-cup</ref> On the other hand, [[Los Angeles]] issued notice of affordable transportation costs and regular transit to and from the [[SoFi Stadium]], along with region transit.<reF>https://www.metro.net/riding/world-cup/</ref> Los Angeles is also due to host the [[2028 Summer Olympics]]. While the opening match was played in a full stadium, the second match showed thousands of empty seats, again raising concerns about high ticket prices. In an official statement regarding the empty seats, FIFA said this was due to "several ticketed fans standing in concourses rather than staying in their assigned seats".<ref>{{Cite web |date=June 12, 2026 |title=Fifa release statement after World Cup match sees thousands of empty seats |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/fifa-world-cup-south-korea-czech-republic-empty-seats-ticket-prices-b2994862.html |access-date=June 12, 2026 |website=The Independent |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Siniawski |first1=Natalia |last2=Lo Bianco |first2=Miguel |date=June 12, 2026 |title=Empty seats at World Cup match renews concerns over ticket prices |newspaper=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/empty-seats-world-cup-match-renews-concerns-over-ticket-prices-2026-06-12/}}</ref>

A 2025 travel ban and its December expansion barred ordinary citizens of Haiti, Iran, Ivory Coast, and Senegal from obtaining visas to attend matches, though players, team staff, and their immediate relatives were exempted.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Abnos |first=Alexander |date=December 17, 2025 |title=World Cup countries Senegal and Côte d'Ivoire among additions to Trump travel ban |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/dec/16/world-cup-travel-ban-senegal-cote-divoire |access-date=December 17, 2025 |work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> A visa bond policy requiring deposits of up to $15,000 from fans of five African qualified nations was suspended in May 2026 for ticket holders.<ref>{{Cite news |date=May 13, 2026 |title=Fans from five African World Cup countries will no longer face $15,000 bond to enter US |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2026/may/13/world-cup-bonds-for-travelers-suspended |access-date=May 17, 2026 |work=The Guardian |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Somali referee [[Omar Abdulkadir Artan]] was denied entry to the United States in June 2026 despite holding a valid visa, and FIFA removed him from its roster.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/world-cup-2026/2026/0609/1577468-somali-world-cup-referee-denied-us-entry/| title=Somali World Cup referee denied US entry|website=RTÉ.ie|date=June 9, 2026}}</ref> [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Homeland Security]] officials also said that customs processing could be halted at airports in [[Sanctuary city|sanctuary host cities]] and that [[United States Immigration and Customs Enforcement|ICE]] personnel may be present at matches; workers at [[SoFi Stadium]] authorized a strike over pay and immigration enforcement concerns before reaching a settlement days ahead of the venue's first match.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lenthang |first1=Marlene |last2=Cohen |first2=Rebecca |date=June 9, 2026 |title=Workers at Los Angeles stadium hosting World Cup matches reach tentative agreement after authorizing strike |work=NBC News |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/workers-los-angeles-stadium-hosting-world-cup-matches-reach-tentative-rcna348582 |access-date=June 10, 2026}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=SoFi Stadium workers reach tentative deal days before World Cup matches |work=Associated Press |date=June 9, 2026 |url=https://apnews.com/article/world-cup-los-angeles-sofi-stadium-workers-a25f17dfdc4172a585880834a252728b |access-date=June 10, 2026}}</ref> Cape Verde's goalkeeper [[Vozinha]]'s mother was issued a last-minute visa to travel and see her son play in their second game.<Ref>https://sports.ndtv.com/fifa-world-cup-2026/from-visa-heartbreak-to-miami-suite-how-cabo-verde-keeper-vozinhas-mother-made-it-to-fifa-world-cup-11669334</ref>

[[Iran at the FIFA World Cup|Iran's participation]] was initially in question due to complications arising from the the [[2026 Iran war]]. The [[Football Federation Islamic Republic of Iran|Football Federation of Iran]] warned that it would boycott the December 2025 draw after its president was denied a U.S. visa, prompting Iranian officials to request that the United States be removed as a host. Iran subsequently negotiated with FIFA and the U.S. government to participate after receiving several concessions, including the relocation of its base camp from Arizona to [[Tijuana]], Mexico, allocation of U.S. visas for players and "vital staff" and a commitment that the [[Lion and Sun flag]], due to its association with the [[Iranian opposition]], would be banned from stadia. Despite the ban, Lion and Sun flags and memorabilia were displayed by supporters during Iran's opening match of the tournament.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bushnell |first=Henry |last2=Whitwell |first2=Laurie |date=June 15, 2026 |title=Pre-revolutionary flags spotted, anthem booed at Iran’s World Cup opener |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/7364659/2026/06/15/iran-world-cup-first-game-flags-anthem/ |access-date=June 21, 2026 |work=[[The New York Times]] |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Taxin |first1=Amy
 |last2=Ding |first2=Jaimie |title=Iranian supporters display pre-revolutionary flag at World Cup match amid FIFA restrictions |url=https://apnews.com/article/0ebcfd4931c65d9a51090290ca9d7805 |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=June 16, 2026
 |access-date=June 21, 2026}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Issenberg |first=Sasha |last2=Miller |first2=Daniel |date=June 21, 2026 |title=FIFA plays flag football against Iranian protesters |url=https://www.politico.com/live-updates/2026/06/21/world-cup-2026/battle-iran-lion-sun-flag-fifa-ban-00969215 |access-date=June 21, 2026 |website=[[Politico]] |language=en}}</ref> Other requests that were denied included relocating matches from the United States to Mexico, banning [[pride flags]] and granting visa clearances for Iranian fans.<ref>{{cite news |title=Iran says World Cup base moved to Mexico from US |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cx21e47e214o |last=Hudson |first=Elizabeth |agency=BBC |date=May 24, 2026 |access-date=May 25, 2026}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=World Cup tickets for Iran fans revoked days before tournament, says country's federation |url=https://www.france24.com/en/sport/20260609-world-cup-tickets-for-iran-fans-revoked-days-before-tournament-says-ffiri-federation |agency=France24 |date=June 9, 2026}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Palmer |first=Poppy-Jay St |date=May 12, 2026 |title=Iran asks FIFA to ban Pride flags at its World Cup matches |url=https://www.thepinknews.com/2026/05/12/iran-fifa-world-cup-pride-flag/ |access-date=June 16, 2026 |website=PinkNews |language=en-US}}</ref> Upon the team's arrival at its training base in Tijuana, players wore lapel pins bearing the number "168" in honor of the victims of [[2026 Minab school attack|Minab school attack]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc7ny.com/post/irans-world-cup-players-wear-pins-for-victims-deadly-strike-on-school-as-they-arrive-mexico/19258775/|title=Iran's World Cup players wear pins for victims of deadly strike on school as they arrive in Mexico|date=June 8, 2026|website=ABC7 New York}}</ref> Critics have argued that the political circumstances surrounding the tournament undermined FIFA's "Football Unites the World" message.<ref>{{Cite news |date=March 17, 2026 |title=World Cup 2026: Is the US-Iran war an ethical tipping point? |url=https://www.dw.com/en/world-cup-2026-is-the-us-iran-war-an-ethical-tipping-point/a-76300631 |access-date=May 2, 2026 |work=Deutsche Welle |last=Harding |first=Jonathan}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=March 25, 2026 |title=A host nation at war with a participant: uncertainty and tension swirl around soccer's World Cup |url=https://www.uts.edu.au/news/2026/03/a-host-nation-at-war-with-a-participant-uncertainty-and-tension-swirl-around-soccers-world-cup |access-date=May 2, 2026 |work=UTS}}</ref> Iran further criticized the discrimination they face in travel arranged to and forth from the base camp in Mexico to California and Washington in an appeal to FIFA.<ref> Iran slams US 'discriminatory treatment' over World Cup visa refusals - https://www.scmp.com/sport/football/article/3356209/iran-slams-us-discriminatory-treatment-over-world-cup-visa-refusals
</ref>

Iran and Egypt urged FIFA to prevent [[LGBTQ movements|LGBTQ]]-related activities linked to the Seattle match, which had been designated a "[[Pride Night#FIFA World Cup|Pride Match]]" by local organizers.<ref>{{cite news |title=Iran threatens to stop World Cup games if faced with unauthorised flags or slogans |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/iran-threatens-stop-world-cup-games-if-faced-with-unauthorised-flags-or-slogans-2026-06-10/ |work=Reuters |date=June 10, 2026}}</ref> In addition, the Spanish group [[CitizenGO]] gathered nearly 123,000 signature on a petition urging FIFA to withdraw the designation, under the pretext of grievances against soccer bodies punishing [[Christian]] messaging.<Ref>https://www.aciafrica.org/news/22491/nearly-123000-sign-petition-urging-fifa-to-remove-lgbt-pride-match-designation-from-egypt-iran-world-cup-fixture</ref>

